#### Tr-3: Public Transit, Cycling, and Walkability
*Strategy:* Research + Navigate
*See also:* Li-5: Planning Trips (for transit in unfamiliar cities), C-4: Advocating for Change (for local transit advocacy)
*My Man Jeeves:* _It would appear that the United States has devoted the better part of seventy years to constructing an infrastructure that assumes every adult to be in possession of a motor car. The consequence, one might observe, is a country in which not driving is regarded as a personal failing rather than a design outcome. In cities where functional transit, cycling infrastructure, and walkable neighborhoods exist, car-free or car-light living saves thousands of dollars per year and improves health outcomes measurably. In cities where these things do not exist, the absence is a policy choice, not an inevitability — and it can be altered at the local level, by those who present themselves at the relevant meetings._
*The spec:*
::: prompt
I want to [reduce my car dependence / go car-free / understand
my transit options / make my commute better / advocate for
better infrastructure in my area].
My location: [city, neighborhood]
My situation: [commute distance, family needs, mobility constraints,
current transportation mix]
Please help me:
1. Map my realistic options — what can I actually do
   without a car, and where are the gaps?
2. Calculate the money I'd save by [specific change:
   dropping a second car, biking to work, using transit]
3. Tell me what infrastructure exists in my area
   that I might not know about — bike lanes, bus routes,
   car-share programs, e-bike incentives
4. If I want to advocate for better options: who decides
   transportation policy in my city, and what has worked elsewhere?
:::
*What to do with the output:* Save the cost comparison to your phone — that number is your motivation on cold mornings. Start with one trip per week. Replace one car trip with transit, cycling, or walking. The compound health benefit is real — a 2023 BMJ study found that cycling to work reduced all-cause mortality risk by 20% and cancer risk by 16%.[^tr3-1] The financial benefit is calculable: the AAA estimates the average cost of car ownership at $12,182/year. Every trip you don't drive reduces that number.

::: science
The [Strong Towns](https://www.strongtowns.org/) movement has documented that car-dependent suburban development is financially insolvent in most American cities — the infrastructure maintenance costs exceed the tax revenue generated by the development pattern. Walkable, mixed-use neighborhoods generate more tax revenue per acre and cost less to maintain. This is not an ideology. It is municipal accounting.[^tr3-2]
:::


::: fairness
Transit access is deeply unequal. Wealthier neighborhoods get better service. Car-dependent design punishes the people who can least afford cars. If your Agent's transit advice assumes a city with a subway, say so: _"I live in [rural/suburban area] where there is no public transit. What are my realistic alternatives to driving for every trip?"_
:::


<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED: E-bike incentives and adoption. Multiple states and cities offer rebates ($200-$1,500) for e-bike purchases. E-bikes have been the fastest-growing category of electric vehicle in the US, outselling electric cars in 2022. For commutes under 10 miles, they are faster than cars in traffic, cheaper than any other motorized option, and zero-emission. The entry should point to local incentive programs. -->

<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED (HUMAN CONDITION): Car culture as American identity. The car is freedom, independence, adulthood in American mythology. Suggesting alternatives triggers identity resistance, not just practical objections. The entry should respect this while presenting the data. Some people love driving. Some people love their commute. The entry is for the people who don't — and there are more of them than the car commercials suggest. -->

[^tr3-1]: Celis-Morales, C.A. et al. (2017). "Association between active commuting and incident cardiovascular disease, cancer, and mortality." _BMJ_, 357, j1456.

[^tr3-2]: Marohn, C.L. (2020). _Strong Towns: A Bottom-Up Revolution to Rebuild American Prosperity._ John Wiley & Sons.

