#### Tr-4: Air Travel
*Strategy:* Prepare + Assert
*See also:* Li-5: Planning Trips (for trip planning broadly), IRL-3: First-Time Situations (for first-time flyers)
*My Man Jeeves:* _One might characterize air travel as a system that charges variable prices for the same seat, enforces rules that shift by airline, route, and day of the week, and operates under federal consumer protection laws that most passengers have not had occasion to read. The airline is aware of one's fare class, one's rebooking options, and the compensation it owes. The passenger, as a general rule, is aware of a confirmation number. An Agent, it would appear, has access to the same regulations the airline's customer service team consults — which places one in the rather more agreeable position of being able to cite them as well._
*The spec:*
::: prompt
I need help with air travel.
My situation: [booking a flight / flight was canceled or delayed /
lost luggage / denied boarding / navigating TSA or customs for
the first time / dealing with flight anxiety / understanding
my consumer rights]
Details: [describe — dates, airline, route, what happened]
Please help me:
1. [If booking]: Find the best strategy for my route and dates —
   when to book, what fare class to look for, what to avoid
2. [If disrupted]: What compensation or rebooking am I legally entitled to?
   Cite the specific regulation (DOT rules for US carriers,
   EC 261/2004 for EU routes)
3. [If first time]: Walk me through the entire airport process
   from arrival to boarding — TSA, customs, gates, boarding groups
4. [If anxious]: Give me evidence-based techniques for managing
   flight anxiety, and tell me what turbulence actually is
Give me the practical answer, not the airline's preferred answer.
:::
*What to do with the output:* For disruptions: know your rights before you get in line. The DOT requires airlines to rebook you on the next available flight at no additional cost for cancellations. For delays over 3 hours on international flights arriving in the EU, EC 261/2004 entitles you to compensation of €250-€600 depending on distance. Airlines do not volunteer this information. You must ask. The specific regulation number is your leverage.

::: tip
_"My flight was [canceled / delayed X hours]. The airline is offering [voucher / rebooking on a later flight]. What am I actually entitled to under DOT regulations, and what should I say at the counter?"_
:::


::: also
Checking current information requires web search, which is free in Gemini, ChatGPT, and Copilot. In Claude, web search requires the paid tier. See [Appendix G](06-appendix-g-feature-table.xhtml).
:::


::: science
Flight anxiety affects an estimated 25-30% of adults to some degree (Oakes & Bor, 2010). The fear is disproportionate to the risk — flying is statistically the safest form of transportation per mile traveled. Cognitive behavioral techniques (particularly exposure-based approaches) are the most effective treatment. Your Agent can walk you through a pre-flight anxiety protocol that a therapist might assign as homework.[^tr4-1]
:::


::: fairness
TSA procedures are opaque by design and anxiety-producing by experience. The process is straightforward once you know it, but knowing it requires either having done it before or having someone explain it. First-time flyers, particularly adults who did not grow up traveling, face a learning curve that is class-coded — people do not admit they have never been through airport security because it marks them. Your Agent can walk you through every step with zero judgment.
:::


